1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 e6 $6 {It is my firm understanding that prior to discussing the mainlines, everyone who's studying a new opening should see how the sidelines are punished. This is the case for two reasons. First of all, it is important to appreciate what ideas we have. Clearly, it's exactly against the sidelines that you get to see all the advantages of our setup most explicitly. Secondly, if you play a new variation, your opponents might want to counter-surprise you and play some sideline to avoid your potential targeted preparation against them specifically. So, here we go, 3...e6. A dumb-looking move, but it was tried by Firouzja and Tari among others!} ( Nf6 $2 {This terrible move and its consequences look very similar to what is discussed after 3...e6 4.Be2 Nf6, but let's make a couple moves anyway.} 4. e5 $1 Nfd7 5. d4 e6 {At this point, it is perfectly possible (and strong) to play 6.c3, when after 6...c5 we transpose to 3...e6 4.Be2 Nf6. However, there's one more powerful idea available.} 6. c4 $1 {I would call this a novelty if it hadn't been played by a 700-rated player back in 2011.} dxc4 7. Bxc4 Nb6 8. Bd3 $16 {This position reminds me of some terrible version of QGA with 3.e4 Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 5.Bxc4, where White gives up the d5-square but gains a large space advantage. We will continue with Nc3, O-O, Bg5, Qe2-e4 or Bc2-Qd3, Rad1, etc. At this point, I am happy to call White's position overwhelming.}  ) 4. Be2 $5 {This rare idea, used by Shoppen against Gavrilesku, seems most promising to me. We are not deciding yet what to do with the structure and we are not committing the knight to c3 or d2. Now, it's up to Black to figure out what to do.} ( 5. Nbd2 {Is the main move, but after} c5 6. d4 ( 7. exd5 exd5 8. d4 {Is, again, a transposition to the Tarrach French with 3...c5 4.exd5 exd5.}  ) cxd4 {Is a transposition to the Tarrasch French, which might be fine with some of you, but not necessarily everyone.}  ) ( 5. Nc3 {Is what Alekseenko and Van Foreest did, but I feel this defeats the purpose of playing 3.d3. As I explained in the intro, the advantage of 3.d3 compared to 3.Nc3, for example, is that we're not committing the knight yet. So, now the have the Two Knights with a weird inclusion of d2-d3 and ...e7-e6. For instance, after} d4 6. Ne2 c5 7. g3 Nc6 8. Bg2 e5 {I find Black's position rather reasonable. Sure, White gets the KIA type of a game, but it's not necessarily what we want, given how pieces are positioned here.}  ) Nf6 ( c5 5. exd5 exd5 6. d4 {See what I did? I just condemned 4.Nd2 since after 4...c5 it's a Tarrasch French. Instead, I am looking to play the Exchange French, but after the much better circumstances. Basically, we have the position after 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 exd5 4.Nf3 c5 5.Be2 in front of us, and this position is considered rather beneficial for White, especially compared to the line 4...Nf6 5.Bd3 c5 6.O-O where Black has an additional idea of 6...c4. I don't really think we need that much theory here, let's just look at the model game.} Nc6 ( c4 $2 {One thing you need to know is that with the bishop on e2, compared to the bishop on d3, this is just a terrible idea.} 7. b3 $1 cxb3 8. axb3 Nf6 9. O-O Bd6 10. c4 $16 O-O 11. c5 Bc7 12. b4 {Black's position is horrendous.}  ) 7. O-O Nf6 8. Nc3 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Be7 10. Bf4 O-O 11. Qd3 Qb6 12. Nb3 {White is now starting to attack the d-pawn. As the great Dane Bent Larsen said, it's best not to block, but instead to attack and win the isolated pawns!} d4 13. Nb5 Nd5 14. Bg3 Rd8 15. Rad1 Be6 16. N5xd4 Ndb4 17. Qe4 Bd5 18. Qg4 Bf6 19. c4 Nxd4 20. Nxd4 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Rxd4 22. Rxd4 Qxd4 23. Qxd4 Bxd4 24. Rd1 Bxb2 25. Bf3 $18 {After some complications, the game got straight into a winning endgame. The White bishops are simply raging!} Bf6 26. Bxb7 Rd8 27. Rxd8+ Bxd8 28. c5 Ba5 29. a3 Nd3 30. Bd6 g5 31. Kf3 Nf4 32. Ke4 Ne6 33. Kd5 h5 34. Bc8 Nc7+ 35. Kc6 Ne8 36. Be7 g4 37. Bd7 Ng7 38. Kb7 f5 39. c6 Kf7 40. Bb4 {1-0 (39) Voitsekhovsky,S (2522) -Isajevsky,A (2417) Kazan 2009}  ) ( Nd7 {If Black just chooses to keep the tension, we can take advantage of the fact the knight isn't on c3 by means of} 5. O-O Bd6 6. c4 $1 $146 {when we grab some neat space advantage in the center. For example, after} Ngf6 7. Nc3 dxe4 8. dxe4 Qc7 ( O-O $4 9. Qxd6  ) 9. h3 $5 {we prevent ...Ng4 and make sure the h2-pawn never hangs. Now, the natural plan would be Qc2, Be3, Rad1, Rd2/d3, Rfd1, etc. Black's c8-bishop definitely doesn't appear quite happy here!} O-O 10. Qc2 b6 {The most logical idea, since the bishop needs to be activated. Yet, after} 11. Be3 Bb7 12. Rad1 {It's not so easy for Black to play this position since ... c6-c5 is barely ever good due to Nb5!, while after} a6 {he is losing too much time and White gets a grip with} 13. Qd2 $1 Be7 14. e5 $1 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. Bxb6 $16 {With a pawn structure this bad, Black will be much worse pretty much forever.}  ) 5. e5 Nfd7 6. d4 c5 7. c3 {Is a very good type of French, because we didn't have to play either Nbd2, which prevents the natural development Be3-Nd2, or Nc3, which makes it impossible to go c2-c3. Now, Black has no pressure on the d4-pawn whatsoever, his position is very passive. In the French proper it's not something White can achieve, since 3.Nc3 or 3.Nd2 are more or less forced move as the e4-pawn is hanging. Here though, we get all we want!} Be7 8. O-O Nc6 9. Re1 {As I explain, 9.Be3 seems most natural to me, but this move is also totally okay. White is preparing to meet ...f7-f6 by putting the rook on the e-file. At the same time, he is freeing up the f1-square for the b1-knight.} ( 10. Be3 O-O 11. Nbd2 {Seems like a more natural way of playing to me. Later, we can plan Re1, Nf1-g3-h5, maybe h2-h4 and Ng5, etc with immense attacking potential on the kingside. Black cannot get counterplay with ...f7-f6 at this point, so we are much better.} f6 $2 ( cxd4 {An attempt to improve on 10...f6, since the c5-pawn wouldn't hang now.} 12. cxd4 f6 13. exf6 Nxf6 14. Ne5 {We will follow up with Ndf3, Qb3, Bd3, Rac1, etc. Black is definitely not happy with the arising position, for example} Bd7 15. Ndf3 Bd6 16. Qb3 {And White is already creating threats, forcing the opponent to resort to ugly moves like ...Rb8 or . ..Qc7. Our initiative is growing big time.}  ) 12. exf6 Nxf6 ( Bxf6 13. dxc5 $16 {Is just a free pawn}  ) 13. dxc5 $16  ) a5 $6 {Now the b5-square is also rather weak.} 10. Na3 $1 cxd4 11. cxd4 Nb6 12. Nb5 $1 {The knight will be a massive pain for Black to deal with. Whenever the dark-squared bishops are traded, the d6-square will turn into a juicy outpost.} Bd7 13. h4 {It definitely makes perfect sense to grab more space on the kingside and prepare either h4-h5 or Ng5/Bg5.} ( 14. Bf4 O-O 15. Nd6 {Also looks rather promising}  ) h6 14. h5 Rc8 15. a3 a4 16. Bd2 Nc4 17. Bxc4 dxc4 18. Nc3 {This isn't as precise, but White still kept the better position and later went on to win a nice game. 1-0 (38) Blumel,O (2208) -Hausner,I (2441) Stare Mesto 2003} ( 19. Nd6+ $1 {Was just positionally crushing here, the point being that after} Bxd6 20. exd6 O-O 21. Bc3 {The White knight is coming to e5 - the square is available now! - and the rook will get to the third rank via e3-g3. Black will get mated shortly.}  )  *

