1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 Qc7 $5 {This rare move has been played 17 times only (and mostly in blitz/rapid) , but it has been tried by GMs exclusively and was recently recommended in Ramdaldi's book on the Caro-Cann publsihed by Thinkers Publishing. So, I definitely think it deserves some rather serious coverage.} 4. Nc3 {After all, the move ...Qc7 must have some disadvantages. One of them is that the d5-pawn isn't protected as well as Black wants it to be, so we are immediately hitting it!} dxe4 {This is the move that was played more or less exclusively (by players like Fedoseev, Melkumyan, Perez, Shimanov, etc) and one suggested by Rambaldi in his book. Now, I would like to offer you two possible solutions.} ( Nf6 $2 {As usual, this is just bad since we will now gain the time by attacking that knight.} 5. e5 Nfd7 6. d4 e6 7. Be3 {We have some French-type position, but the move ...Qc7 is making Black's task a lot tougher since now ...c6-c5 always runs into ideas like Nb5.} c5 ( Be7 {Instead, Black can as well simply choose to develop, but after} 8. Bd3 O-O $2 {His king will be too weak. Moves like Ng5 look very attractive, but it's even more brutal to immediately launch the onslaughter with} 9. h4 $1 {Now the Greek Gift is around the corner, while after} f5 ( c5 $4 {In the event of a random move, we win with} 10. Bxh7+ Kxh7 11. Ng5+ Kg6 12. Qg4 $18 {Standard pattern, make sure to know it!}  ) 10. Ng5 {White's attack is absolutely decisive. Qh5 is coming, there's no way to defend the e6-pawn, while ...Bxg5 will open up the h-file. Black can as well resign with a clear conscience :)}  ) 8. Nb5 $1 Qd8 9. dxc5 Nxc5 ( Bxc5 $2 10. Bxc5 Nxc5 11. Nd6+ $18 {Is also crushing, of course}  ) 10. c4 $1 $16 {And the position is simply falling apart.}  ) ( e6 {Was tried in one game by a 2400-rated player, but it's quite poor, too, since now the c8-bishop is the saddest piece in the world.} 5. g3 $1 {This is definitely the right way for White to develop.} b6 6. Bg2 Bb7 7. O-O Nd7 {At this point, White already had a decisive advantage that should have been exploited with} 8. d4 ( 9. exd5 $1 cxd5 10. Bf4 Qc5 $1 {The only way to stop Nb5} ( Qd8 11. Nb5 $18 {Nd6 and Nc7 cannot be stopped.}  ) 11. d4 Qc6 $1 {At this point, White has a plethora of attacking possibilities, the most interesting and direct one being} ( Qc8 12. Nb5 $1 $18  ) 12. Nxd5 $5 Qxd5 $4 ( exd5 13. Re1+ Be7 14. c4 $1 {Having sacrificed a piece for a mere pawn, we are now putting the rest of the board on fire. You can investigate a bit deeper, but take my word: this is dead-lost. And it wasn't even neccessary to sacrifice unless you wanted to!}  ) 13. Nh4 $18  ) a6 9. Bf4 Bd6 10. e5 $6 $14 {White's development is so much better, so the idea of closing the position down seems erroneous to me. White is still massively for choice due to his extra space, but I think it was possible to handle this much better.. 1-0 (50) Stukan,M (2292) -Nomin Erdene,D (2417) Graz 2020}  ) 5. dxe4 $5 ( 6. Nxe4 {Is the move that was chosen by most GMs.} Nf6 7. Qe2 {This position greatly resembles the line of Two Knights with 3...dxe4 4.Nxe4 Nf6. Here, moves d2-d3 and ...Qc7 are included, which I think helps White, since our queenside can be developed more easily and Black doesn't have the idea ...Qd8-d5!} Nxe4 ( Nbd7 8. g3 Nxe4 9. Qxe4 Nf6 {Is just a transposition. By the way, Rambaldi doesn't consider Qe5 here, he only analyzes 9.Qe2 (which, by the way, should also give some edge!) .}  ) 8. Qxe4 Nd7 9. g3 Nf6 10. Qe5 $1 {Does not lead to an equal position, at least anytime soon. Say, after} Qxe5+ 11. Nxe5 Nd5 12. f4 $1 {Black cannot play ...e7-e5, which means White will keep the advantage due to his extra space.}  ) e5 {Let me mention Rambaldi's evalution and description of this position. He says that the position reminds of the Philidor defense with the only (significant) difference being that the d4 and d6-pawns have already been traded, which means Black doesn't suffer from lack of space. He mentions it's vital to play carefully since the development is subpar, but concludes that Black should be fine. Let's try to challenge this evaluation a bit!} 6. Bc4 {Of course, this is the most natural, active and logical move.} b5 {I would not go in great depth here, let me just try to challenge the line from Rambaldi's book.} 7. Bb3 h6 $1 ( Nf6 $2 8. Ng5 {Is immediately bad}  ) 8. O-O Nd7 {At this point, I believe, White has several attractive ideas.} 9. a4 {Is the calmer continuation.} ( 10. Nxb5 $5 cxb5 11. Qd5 {If we don't get advantage, at least we can scare Black!} Nb6 12. Qxb5+ Bd7 13. Qxe5+ Qxe5 14. Nxe5 Be6 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Ng6 Rh7 17. Nxf8 Kxf8 {Rambaldi says White has no reasons to claim advantage, but after} 18. b3 $1 {I think he does. We will play c2-c4, f2-f3 or f2-f4 and three passed pawns as well as the powerful dark-squared bishop should be clearly better than two knights, in my opinion! While the engine is claiming it's better equal and slightly better for White, I think Black really has to be careful here, as in the foreseeable future the pawns can simply smash the opponent.}  ) b4 10. Ne2 Ba6 11. Re1 O-O-O {Rambaldi believes this position is reasonable for Black, but I wouldn't jump at a conclusion like this, since the queenside structure is very questionable. For instance, after} 12. Bd2 $1 Nc5 13. Ng3 h5 14. Ng5 $5 {Black to solve a number of long-term issues.} h4 15. Nf1 Nxb3 16. cxb3 {The c-file is weak, the squares on c4 and c5 are a problem, ideas like Rc1, Qc2, Ne3-c4, etc are hanging in the air. This is just SO dangerous! And if this position isn't up to your taste, make sure to take on e4 with the knight and press in a somewhat better calm endgame!}  *

