1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 g6 {A rather passive-looking move, which however does make quite a lot of sense, since the White pawn is on d3. I think we can tackle this idea in two attractive ways, let's dive right in!} 4. Nbd2 {This is the move you'd make if you are looking for a calm, no-risk-involved type of advantage.} ( 5. e5 {Is also a very decent fighting move. The positions are definitely better for White, but I think he has a bit less control than after 4.Nbd2, so I won't go in too much detail here.} Bg7 6. d4 f6 7. exf6 Nxf6 {This is the main position you'll be getting.} ( exf6 {isn't that great} 8. c4 $1 Ne7 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O Bf5 11. Nc3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 {This position is, again, slightly better for White. But again, I like the idea of playing 4.Nbd2! better, so let's rather focus on that.}  ) 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O Bg4 10. Nbd2 Nbd7 {Here, White had a great opportunity, namely} 11. c3 ( 12. Ng5 $1 Bf5 13. Bd3 {And the e6-square would have been way too weak and lonely. Instead, White didn't find this and later Black went on to win a nice game.}  ) Qc7 12. h3 {0-1 (40) Chigaev,M (2644) -Lenderman,A (2648) chess24.com INT 2020}  ) Bg7 5. d4 $5 ( 6. g3 {Is the most frequent move, but I personally am not a fan of giving up so much space, since Black now has} e5 $1 {Actually, it's not bad for White at all, he can still fight for the advantage, but I personally don't really like this plan as much as other possibilities that are available here.} 7. Bg2 Ne7 8. O-O O-O 9. c3 {The knight on e7 is very ugly, so White is a touch better. You can study Demchenko's games to get a better feel for the arising positions!}  ) dxe4 6. Nxe4 Nf6 {Typically, this position is reached via 1.e4 g6 2.d4 c6 with an extra tempo for White (he usually has the move h2-h3 included) , but I don't think it's a big deal. Anyway, we will be somewhat better!} ( Bg4 {Doesn't yield anything, we can play c2-c3. Even though, actually, there's an even better solution:} 7. Bc4 $1 {Now, the threat of Ng5! is too strong, so Black has to give up his bishop pair right away.} Bxf3 ( Nf6 8. Neg5 O-O $2 9. Nxf7 Rxf7 10. Bxf7+ Kxf7 11. Ne5+ $18  ) 8. Qxf3 Nf6 9. c3 $16 {With the typical long-lasting advantage.}  ) 7. Nxf6+ exf6 ( Bxf6 $6 {It is well-known that it's dangerous to capture with the bishop since Bh6! is now always available. However, I'd actually rather not hurry with that move.} 8. c3 $5 ( 9. Bh6 c5 $1 {is not that clear, since the b2-pawn is now hanging (though objectively White is still better, but why give up control?)}  ) O-O 9. Bh6 Re8 10. Bc4 {We will just quietly develop and try to use our extra space. Likely, we'll also get the bishop pair since Black might at some point go ...Bg4 and trade on f3. This advantage is by no means decisive or huge, but it's definitely a very pleasant one!}  ) 8. Bc4 {I think the bishop is placed best exactly on this diagonal, since it's making it hard for Black to play ...Be6 while also pressuring f7.} O-O 9. O-O {We are looking at a very typical structure, but at a rather new sequence of moves with only 2 games in the database. Let's quote the game of highest-rated players who got here, where White unfortunately lost, and undestand what went wrong and what he should have done instead.} Nd7 ( b5 {Based on our comments a move later, you might ask why Black wouldn't play this move right away. Well, unfortunately, after} 10. Be2 {a2-a4! on the next move simply does a ton of damage to his structure,} Nd7 11. a4 $1 b4 12. a5 $1 $16 {And this is an extremely painful position for Black to find himself in!}  ) 10. a4 $1 {Is the idea I like best, as it stops ...b7-b5.} ( 11. c3 b5 {I don't think there was any need whatsoever to allow for this space-grabbing activity.} 12. Bb3 a5 13. a4 Nb6 14. Re1 {I'd say here Black is already doing alright (though, of course, not ever more than that!)} Bb7 $6 {The bishop should have rather been developed to e6 or f5 after ...Re8.} 15. h4 $5 h6 $2 ( Re8 $1 {Black should have ignored White's play instead of weakening his structure even more.}  ) 16. h5 $1 Kh7 17. Nh4 {White missed the best continuation, but still got a large initiative, even though later he lost. Still, the line is very attractive for us!: 0-1 (47) Martinez Reyes,P (2422) -Sunilduth Lyna,N (2618) chess.com INT 2020} ( 18. Qd3 $1 f5 19. Ne5 {Would have crushed Black more or less right away!}  )  ) a5 11. Re1 Nb6 12. Bb3 Nd5 {In such structures, it's well-known that the inclusion of a2-a4 and ...a7-a5 is supposed to be in Black's favour, as now it's never possible to kick the knight out with c2-c4 since then the b4-square will become an outpost. However, I still like White a lot. Basically, all we need is trade down a bit.} 13. Bd2 Bf5 14. h3 Qc7 15. c4 $1 {Nevertheless!} Nf4 ( Nb4 16. Bxb4 axb4 17. c5 $1 $16 {We would be happy to trade the bishops as well. The b4-pawn is now separated from the rest of the army and is clearly weak, White is about to win it with Qd2 or Rac1-c4.}  ) 16. Bc2 Bxc2 17. Qxc2 $14 {This is not a large advantage, but again, I fail to believe Black can ever fully equalize.}  *

