1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 Bg4 $5 {The second most popular move. Black plays in a manner similar to the line of Two Knights where he meets 2.Nf3 d5 3.Nc3 with Bg4. However, I believe, it's a suspicious decision here, since the fact we haven't yet played Nc3 really benefits White - the knight can easily go to d2 as well in the future. On the other hand, we need to be somewhat more careful in the lines with ...Bh5. Basically, in the Two Knights it's known that to play ...Bh5 is very dangerous because of the concrete threats. Here, though, we're kind of a tempo down, so that idea is more interesting and needs to be studied in-depth.} 4. h3 $1 {It's vital that we chase the bishop immediately. Now, most people have retreated to h5, which makes sense. Instead, taking on f3 is rather compliant.} ( 5. Be2 {To my surprise, the timid bishop move has been White's most popular continuation. However, I don't believe White is getting anywhere after the simple} e6 $11  ) Bh5 {This is the principled though dangerous way to play. Now, 5.Qe2 has been the main move, but I think 5. g4 is a slightly nicer move order that will most likely transpose to 5.Qe2. We just lessen the number of Black's options a bit.} ( Bxf3 5. Qxf3 {Just for your information: in this position, White has been scoring the whopping 77%! The explanation is very simple: since our knight can go d2, Black lacks typical defensive ideas, such as ...Bb4 to pin the knight, or ...d5-d4 to kick it out. Also, we can always transfer it on the kingside a lot faster to generate the initiative and play c2-c3 to cover the d4-square. All in all, this looks really bad.} e6 6. g3 {Most games from this position have been played in 2020, so you'll have to agree to study the COVID-type blitz/rapid games instead of the classical battles! Our plan is very simple: Bg2, O-O, Nd2, then most likely c2-c3, maybe f2-f4 and e4-e5. Let's now study a very instructive model game (btw, in this position, White won ALL 7 games that reached it) .} Nd7 7. Bg2 g6 8. O-O Bg7 9. c3 {White chooses to take it slow} ( 10. exd5 $5 {Is also interesting, because to capture with the e-pawn is clearly dangerous due to Re1, while} cxd5 {allows for the quick breakthrough in the center} 11. c4 $1 Ne7 12. Nc3 {And the center is already under some incredible danger. For instance, after} Ne5 13. Qd1 O-O 14. cxd5 exd5 15. Bf4 Qd7 16. Qd2 $16 {Black's position definitely looks very unattractive given that the e7-knight is heavily restricted, the d5-pawn is under pressure and White's bishops are rather useful.}  ) Ne7 10. Bg5 h6 11. Be3 O-O 12. Nd2 {Next up, we can either play d3-d4, or Qe2 with the idea of f2-f4. By the way, even some queenside play with a2-a4-a5, b2-b4, etc is also very reasonable! As you can see, White has a plethora of options and Black is just defending passively, this is not fun for him at all.} dxe4 $2 13. dxe4 Ne5 14. Qd1 Qc7 15. f4 $1 $16 {Now, things are simply terrible!} Nd7 16. Qe2 Rad8 17. a4 Rfe8 18. e5 Nd5 19. Bf2 h5 20. h4 Ne7 21. Ne4 Nf5 22. a5 {This is the type of a game you want to have. White is just enjoying his time all over the board while Black doesn't have a slighest hope for counterplay. Eventually, White managed to win a lovely game. 1-0 (43) Popov,I (2636) -Deviatkin,A (2436) Moscow 2019}  ) 5. g4 $5 {We are immediately taking the bull by the horns, creating a possibility of playing against that bishop in the future with h3-h4-h5 or Ne5.} ( 6. Qe2 {Gives Black an extra opportunity of taking on f3 (though this would transpose to 4...Bxf3, which we don't mind, but let's not let him have any additional options!)} e6 7. g4 Bg6 {And we transpose} 8. h4 h5 9. Ne5 {Is also worth analyzing, do check it out yourself!} Bh7 10. g5 dxe4 11. Nxf7 $1 {And a ton of fun begins!}  ) Bg6 ( dxe4 $146 {We will study the endgame in the next chapters, let me just say for now that after} 6. dxe4 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 Bg6 8. Bd3 Nf6 9. Nc3 $14 {White gets an even better version of this endgame, since the bishop on g6 is so restricted!}  ) 6. Qe2 {Now, we're reaching a brand-new position that has been reached in less than a dozen games so far. Mostly, the move 6...e6 has been played, but we will also mention other possibilties.} ( 7. Nc3 {Is another perfectly possible move order.}  ) e6 ( Nf6 $6 {As usual, allowing for e4-e5 with a tempo is very risky. By the way, White can also just play Nc3, keeping the tension.} 7. e5 $1 Nfd7 8. h4 $1 {The bishop is a target, which is a very frequent thing in these positions.} h5 ( h6 9. h5 Bh7 10. e6 {is no better for Black than the alternatives. He's doing simply terrible.} fxe6 11. Nc3 $16 { How to get the kingside pieces out?}  ) 9. e6 $1 fxe6 10. Bh3 $1 {g4-g5 is about to follow with a complete squeeze.}  ) 7. h4 h6 ( h5 $146 {No one has ever tried this move, probably because now White has a very promising idea} 8. Ne5 Bh7 ( Ne7 9. Nxg6 Nxg6 10. gxh5 Nxh4 11. Qg4 $16 {Looks rather uncomfortable for Black, too.}  ) 9. g5 {Now, the h5-pawn is hanging.} dxe4 {And here comes the bummer!} ( g6 $4 {is a strategically lost position now that the h7-bishop is dead.}  ) ( Bd6 10. g6 $1 fxg6 11. exd5 cxd5 12. Bh3 $44 {Looks very uncomfortable for Black as well. Generally, you might really want to pay attention to this g5-g6! idea, since it's a very frequent positional sacrifice when the bishop is stuck on h7.}  ) 10. Nxf7 $1 {Boom! Black might as well lose conscience, since now his king is dragged into the open space and there's no way he can ever get active.} Kxf7 11. Qxh5+ g6 ( Ke7 {I guess it's also possible to retreat, but after} 12. dxe4 Qe8 13. Qg4 $40 {it feels to me White will find the arising position extremely easy to play, since Nc3, Be3-f4, O-O-O, f2-f4-f5, etc are coming and there's no telling how Black should be getting the g8-knight and the f8-bishop in the game.}  ) 12. Qg4 exd3 13. Bxd3 $36 {Of course, it is worth exploring and investigating this extremely rich position in more detail. But since it's so fresh, the concrete sequences are somewhat hard to dig. Instead, I'd just rather say Nc3, Be3/f4, O-O-O and h4-h5 are all about to be played, which means Black should be extremely careful not to lose on the spot. On top of that, he still has to figure out why the h7-bishop is supposed to count as an extra piece, how to get the rest of the pieces in the game and where to hide his king given that White can easily play h4-h5 whenever he wishes to do so.}  ) ( dxe4 {It makes sense to open the center up, especially if Black is afraid we will roll on the kingside if the position stays closed. However, now Black's key asset, the d5-pawn, is gone.} 8. dxe4 h5 9. g5 {This is how all games where Black took on e4 went, but White just has a nice spatial advantage and the g6-bishop is still out of play.} Nd7 10. Bf4 $1 {If we stop ...Qc7 and ...Bd6, Black won't be able to get his kingside pieces out.} Qb6 11. c3 $16 {We could have as well sacrificed the b2-pawn, but there's no need. Now, it's totally unclear how the Black pieces plan on coming out, while b2-b4, Nbd2-c4, Rd1, etc are on cards. Looks very bad!}  ) 8. h5 {This idea has been tried once only - by Aronian versus Artemiev back in November of 2019. I believe this fresh idea is extremely interesting, since we are immediately pushing Black back to ropes!} ( 9. Nc3 {Is the main move. We are putting more pressure on the center while also preparing Bd2, O-O-O, g4-g5/h4-h5, etc. I prefer the somewhat more direct approach, though!}  ) Bh7 9. g5 $1 {Again, I go with them most direct approach.} ( 10. Nc3  ) ( 10. Bg2 {Such moves are also rather fascinating and I would strongly encourage you to analyze them on your own to both get a better feel for the arising positions and to have several possibilties, depending on your mood/opponent/tournament situation.}  ) hxg5 10. Nxg5 {Now, the plan is very simple. We'll just go f2-f4, Bg2, Nc3, Bd2/e3, possibly will castle long. The bishop clearly isn't having much fun on f7! We have a brand-new position here, it's possible to analyze several moves, but I would much rather focus on plans and ideas. So, let's dicsuss Aronian's game.} Be7 11. f4 Nd7 12. Bh3 ( 13. Bg2 {Seems to be the more appropriate square for the bishop to me, since there's not enough pressure on e6/f7 after Bh3. Instead, this bishop is putting pressure on the d5-pawn while also keeping the h-file open for our rook. Now, it is EXTREMELY easy for Black to go wrong. For example} Ngf6 ( dxe4 14. dxe4 {Just compare this position to the one in the game! The bishop is clearly much better positioned on g2!}  ) 14. Be3 Qc7 15. Nc3 $16 {And now Black is in some sort of a zugzwang, since castling short is suicidal, while long castling would hang the f7-pawn and the rest of the setup. We, instead, can just castle, push e4-e5 or f4-f5...this is just horrendously bad.} Rc8  ) Qa5+ ( dxe4 $1 13. dxe4 Ngf6 {Now, it would have been the right timing for Black to release the central tension, since the h3-bishop isn't doing much.}  ) 13. Bd2 Qb6 14. Nc3 d4 $2 {A grave strategic mistake, since now White's spatial advantage is undisputable and Black has no opportunities related to the central counterplay.} 15. Nd1 $16 {The game was eventually drawn, but at this point, White is clearly massively for choice. 1/2 (37) Aronian,L (2758) -Artemiev,V (2746) chess.com INT 2019}  *

