1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 dxe4 {Now that we have analyzed literally every single possibility Black could throw at us on move 3, it is the time to discuss the very main line 3...dxe4. What could be more logical than to trade, get the queens off the board and deprive White of castling right?} 4. dxe4 {Let us now have a small chapter where we will discuss how we will be setting our pieces up if Black chooses not to trade here. The probability that he will trade is more or less 99%, but it's good to understand what we will do if he doesn't. For example, in similar endgame-type lines, such as 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.dxc3, Black started coming up with ideas like 6...Qc7, so it makes perfect sense to understand what our setup should look like.} Nd7 {This has been tried in three games so far. Now, White has several promising ways of how to continue.} ( Qc7 {Here, we should rather know another very important and not-so-natural move.} 5. Qd4 $1 $146 {Now, ...e7-e5 is never happening and e4-e5! instead is on cards. Another benefit of this move is that ...Bg4 will no longer be a pin.} ( 6. Bc4 e6 {As I said, I don't think the bishop is that needed on c4.} ( Nd7 7. O-O Ngf6 {Is also something Black can try, even though it's not that attractive an idea.}  )  ) ( 6. Be2 e5 $1 $11 {Is immediately more or less equal. We clearly shouldn't be allowing for ...e7-e5 so easily!}  ) Nf6 ( Bg4 6. Ne5 $1 {And the bishop doesn't even have a comfortable spot to retreat to.} Be6 7. Bf4 $16 {Black needs to lose even more time, while our development is going SO smoothly! His position clearly isn't attractive.}  ) 6. Nc3 e6 {We can push e4-e5 more or less whenever, but I don't want to allow Black to go ...Nd5 too early. Perhaps soon we'll do this, but why hurry?} 7. Bd3 Be7 8. e5 Nd5 9. Qg4 {For example, once he dropped the bishop on e7, e4-e5! became much more powerful since the kingside is under massive pressure now.} O-O ( Kf8 10. O-O Nxc3 11. bxc3 { Is another position where Black is doing quite terrible.}  ) 10. Bh6 $18 {Is a typical way of losing an exchange.}  ) ( Bg4 {Obviously, if Black is to trade queens, he should rather trade himself as opposed to allowing for the trade on d8. Still, someone tried this move 3 times.} 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Ne5 Be6 7. Nd3 $16 {Next up, we go f2-f3, Be3, Nc3 or Nd2. If allowed, Nc5! would hurt Black rather badly, too.}  ) 5. e5 $1 {I love this new idea best. We are stopping ...e7-e5 and are ensuring ourselves of a space advantage. Also, if Black ever wants to go ...e7-e6, which is something he will clearly have to do or else his kingside will be stuck for good, we will occupy the d6-outpost.} ( 6. Bc4 {There's nothing wrong with this move, either, but now after ...e7-e6 the bishop is not positioned optimally since the c4-square is needed for the knight for the route of Nd2-c4-d6! to happen.}  ) e6 6. Be2 Ne7 {Our position is fantastic, but it's important not to handle it carelessly.} 7. Nbd2 $1 ( 8. O-O $4 {would be a large mistake since after} Ng6 $1 {it's rather impossible to defend the e5-pawn and Black is already much better.}  ) Ng6 8. Nc4 {Next up, Nd6 is inevitably coming.} Qc7 9. Nd6+ Bxd6 10. exd6 Qa5+ 11. Qd2 {Of course, it's also perfectly possible to keep the queens as well.} Qxd2+ 12. Bxd2 {In this endgame, White is significantly better thanks to his bishop pair, lead in development, and, most importantly, the powerful d6-pawn. The c8-bishop is rather stuck, but to play . ..e6-e5 isn't easy.} e5 ( O-O 13. h4 $1 {Again, this idea is very powerful, since now the g6-knight is getting relentlessly kicked out around.} h5 14. O-O-O {Besides the obvious slow-improvement type of moves like g2-g3, Bc3, etc, we can also go for the direct assault with Rdg1 and g2-g4! Either way, Black's position is horrendously bad.}  ) 13. h4 $1 h5 14. Bd3 Ndf8 15. Ng5 $16 { Black is not getting out of this bind, his position is very bad.}  *

