1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 dxe4 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 {Alright, now we've made it to the very core position of this database - the classic endgame! Let me give a few more examples of when White might want to go for the endgame while losing the castling rights: 1) 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5, and now both 5.h4 with the same idea and the old 5.e4 Nxc3 6.dxc3 Qxd1 7.Kxd1 result in the same positions, where White gives up his castling rights. Why does he do that? The answer's very simple: he believes the king will be better off on c2 after c2-c3!, since it's already an endgame and there's no need to castle. Instead, castling might even worsen the king's position! There are several other lines, such as 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.Nc3 d5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e3 Nxc3 6.dxc3, or 1.e4 c5 2.f4 d5 3.Bb5+ Bd7 4.Bxd7 Qxd7 5.d3, which I am advocating for in my Anti-Sicilian White repertoire "The Accelerated Rossolimo", where we are inviting Black to take on e4 and d1 and enable us to enjoy a lovely bunch of pawns in the center and where our king will be positioned very nicely. Black often plays in the same way, too! For example, the Philidor defense 1.e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 e5 is based on the same idea - Blacks wants White to trade on d8, since then he intends on playing ...c7-c6 and ...Kc7, hiding his king in a safe spot and hoping to utilize it later on. So, this setup against the Caro shouldn't come across as a complete surprise, either! As we said, our plans for now are Be3, c2-c3, Bc4, Nfd2 and f2-f3, covering the g4-square. The very best move, as I believe, is 5...Nf6, but in this chapter, we will consider Black's alternatives on move 5. In fact, 5...Nf6 even isn't the main move, so we'll have plenty of other work to do before moving on to the main guys 5... Bg4 and 5...Nf6!} g6 {Quite a lot of players, including MVL who did this twice, tried developing the bishop to the long diagonal. However, as practice shows, the bishop isn't well-placed there, since the c3-pawn would be restricting it a lot. In fact, now I like a very interesting idea that doesn't seem obvious at all.} ( Nd7 6. Ne1 $1 {Again, we have only two games in the database at this point, but I strongly believe the knight NEEDS to be re-routed to d3 as soon as possible so that f2-f3 can easily be played!} g6 {As I state when we discuss the move 5...g6, I do not believe the bishop belongs on the long diagonal in such positions, since the c3-pawn is doing too great a job when it comes to restricting it. However, this is exactly the only move Black tried in this position. And the players were very strong - Vladislav Artemiev, one of the very top players, and a very strong and Caro-Cann-savvy Hungarian GM Peter Prohaszka.} 7. Nd3 {This move makes way more sense - why not activate the knight immediately?} ( 8. Nd2 {To me, it seems a bit illogical to first go Ne1 and then leave it there. As we say in Russian, "if you say A, you need to say B", which essentially means one needs to be consistent. This is exactly what I am preaching to my students, both private ones and all people who read my articles/surveys/study my video courses/books. Be consistent! But, on the other hand, who am I to argue with what Aronian does?} f5 $1 {Artemiev handles this very well. As we know based on the positions we see in the line 5...g6 (and hopefully, many readers are aware of classical games of Andresson in the Anti-Grunfeld in the similar structure, etc) , Black is bound to suffer deeply in the long run unless he comes up with a very clear vision of how to generate concrete counterplay. The move ...f7-f5 does exactly that. Since now White's development is rather odd and ugly, Black is rushing to create counterplay.} 9. exf5 gxf5 10. Nc4 e5 11. Nd3 e4 12. Nf4 {It still feels as though White managed to generate a certain amount of pressure, since Black's structure has been somewhat shaken and our f4-knight has an amazing outpost.} b5 {Now, White didn't react properly.} 13. Ne3 ( 14. Na5 $1 {would have been the right way to go, tackling the c6-pawn.} Ne5 15. a4 $1 b4 16. b3 {With a clear advantage due to the better pawn structure and multiple weak squares, such as c4, c5, f4, etc.}  ) Ne5 14. Bd2 ( 15. a4 $1 {Again, it would have been very reasonable to challenge Black's queenside and then play b2-b3 and Bb2.}  ) Nf6 15. Bc3 Bd6 {And here Black even obtained the upper hand, since the bishop isn't placed well on c3.1/2 (38) Aronian,L (2758) -Artemiev,V (2746) chess.com INT 2019}  ) Bg7 8. Nd2 ( 9. a4 $1 {I would prefer not to commit the knight yet, we will see why in a second. Instead, first of all, we grab space, preparing a4-a5, c2-c3, Kc2.} f5 10. exf5 gxf5 11. c3 e5 12. Kc2 {One nice difference between the early Nd2 and the early a4 I see is that now the c1-bishop can come out first, actually! That's why I was hesitant to develop this queenside knight as soon as possible.}  ) f5 $1 {Again, it's fundamental that Black tries to generate counterplay as soon as possible.} 9. f3 $2 {This is lame, now the knight cannot come to f3, Black is immediately doing well.} ( 10. exf5 {White should definitely take, hoping to take advantage of the fact Black has more pawn islands and his pawns are somewhat ovextended/vulnerable.} gxf5  ) Ngf6 10. exf5 gxf5 11. Nc4 Nd5 $13 {I still slightly prefer White, but later Black went on to win a complicated game. Don't wait, take on f5 as soon as your opponent gets this move in!: 0-1 (82) Michalik,P (2595) -Prohaszka,P (2587) chess.com INT 2020}  ) ( f6 {This move makes a fair amount of sense as it tries to prepare ..e7-e5. But, it's not fast enough (we'll see what I mean when we finally get to the discussion of 5...Nf6) , so White keeps his standard pleasant edge.} 6. Bc4 e5 7. a4 Bc5 8. Ke2 {Now it's also perfectly reasonable to develop the king on e2 instead of c2.} Ke7 ( a5 $1 $146 {I believe it's fundamental that Black prevents a4-a5.} 9. Rd1 {First, we let rhe rook out.} Ne7 10. Ne1 $1 {Then we execute this typical idea Nf3-e1-d3, so that the knight is better positioned and f2-f3! can be played. Please note how difficult it is for Black to find good spots for his pieces. Where does the king go? How about the light-squared bishop?} Nd7 11. f3 Ng6 12. Nd3 Bb6 13. g3 $14 {We are ready to both improve the queenside pieces with Be3, Nbd2, etc as well as expand on the kingside with h2-h4. Meanwhile, Black is still longing for counterplay. That's exactly the type of a position we are looking for in this line!}  ) ( Ne7 {Was the only move that has been tried, but Bacrot went on to win a very nice game where Black didn't ever manage to get a slighest bit of activity.}  ) 9. a5 $1 Be6 10. Nbd2 $16 {Black might have prepared the bishop trade, but his g8-knight is still ugly and the a5-pawn is grabbing so much space. This is not fun for him!}  ) 6. Ne5 $1 {Only two games saw this move, but I believe it is best. Why are we making it? Well, the thing is that we want to play Be3, but getting hit by the eventual ...Ng4 is no bueno, so we nee f2-f3 in. But that knight is misplaced on f3! So, we are re-routing the knight.} Bg7 7. Nd3 Nf6 8. f3 O-O 9. a4 {Grabbing space on the queenside is another very typical idea.} ( 10. c3 {Obviously, there's nothing wrong with c2-c3 first. Or with Be3 first, or with something else first - the position is very versatile. Later, we simply want to play Kc2, Be3, Nbd2, a2-a4-a5 and reach a very nice position with pressure on the queenside where the g7-bishop will remain a passive and silent spectator.}  ) Nfd7 10. Bg5 {I am not sure how much I like this move, since the bishop wants to be on e3, anyway. I guess forcing ...Bf6 isn't that bad, just as ...Re8, but the normal Be3 is completely fine as well.} Bf6 11. Be3 Ne5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. c3 Be6 14. Nd2 Nd7 15. Kc2 {Alright, now the optimal setup has been achieved! What do we do next? Next up, we should play either Bc4 to trade the only good bishop Black has and to leave him with a sad useless dark-squared one, or keep rolling with Be2, a4-a5, b2-b4, etc. I prefer the first plan.} Bd6 16. Bc4 $1 {The aforementioned plan in action.} Bxc4 17. Nxc4 Bc7 18. Rhd1 $16 {White has a massive advantage in such positions, but I would suggest we study the rest of the game in more detail when we are discussing the model games at the end of this theoretical work. 1-0 (50) Gavrilescu,D (2473) -Olsen,F (2332) Hamburg 2020}  *

