1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 dxe4 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 Bg4 {There are a few reasons why we will study this move in a separate chapter. The most obvious one is that it is the most popular move in the position by far, so the chances you'll it are rather high. Worth focusing on! And an even more valid reason, to my mind, is that this move stops our typical plan, which is re-routing the ugly-placed f3-knight to d3 via e1 or e5. Fortunately, our play here is still very simple.} 6. Be2 Nd7 {Since Black is interested in castling long fast, this has been the main move. But, to be honest, I don't really see how long castling is supposed to help him THAT much. Fair enough, his king isn't well-placed is the center, even less so on the kingside. On the queenside, instead, it'd help Black stop the invasion and expansion we are planning by means of a4-a5, Nc4, etc. However, his position still won't be fantastic.} ( e6 {This move isn't that silly, but I find the idea of voluntarily giving space up somewhat suspicious (even though it's more justified now, when Black had developed his c8-bishop outside of the pawn chain) .} 7. Ne5 $1 {Again, whenever possible, I improve my f3-knight!} Bxe2+ 8. Kxe2 Nf6 9. f3 $146 {Next up, I am simply looking to play Nbd2-c4, Ne5-d3 if needed, Be3, a2-a4-a5, Rhd1, etc. Later, we can start grabbing space on the kingside with g2-g4-g5, our position is extremely comfortable (and again, we see that this plan is so universal and is met everywhere else throughout the chapter!)} Nbd7 10. Nc4 Bc5 11. a4 Ke7 12. Rd1 Rhd8 13. Nbd2 $16 {Later, Nb3, a4-a5 and bishop somewhere (f4, g5, maybe e3) will be the very natural moves to make. Again, I feel to spot or recognize any kind of counterplay.}  ) ( Nf6 $1 7. Nfd2 $1 {Again, the goal is to improve the f3-knight! I hope that by now, you already recognize this pattern rather distinctively.} Bxe2+ 8. Kxe2 g6 $5 $146 {Could be a very interesting idea. Remember how I kept insisting the bishop doesn't belong on g7? Nope, I didn't change my mind, it definitely doesn't! It's headed elsewhere.} ( e5 9. f3 $14 {I don't want to spend too much ink on discussion of this highly typical position. Let's just keep in mind everything we've said about such positions earlier! a2-a4, Nc4, c2-c3, Be3, Nbd2, a4-a5, Rhd1, etc... Squeeze and enjoy.}  ) 9. f3 Bh6 $1 {As soon as White defended the e4-pawn to later play Nc4, Black makes this important move. Perhaps, this position is as close as he gets to equality in this line, even though after} 10. a4 Nbd7 11. Na3 Nc5 12. Nac4 Ne6 13. Nb3 Bxc1 14. Rhxc1 {I think that White is still slightly for choice, given how active he is on the queenside. a4-a5 is on the way. But, this is definitely the right way for Black to play.}  ) ( Bxf3 {GM Adly and IM Murzin have immediately traded this bishop, avoiding what's about to come up in the mainline. However, I fail to believe that giving the bishop pair up this easily is a good idea.} 7. Bxf3 Nd7 ( e5 {Was also tried, but by players rated below 1700. The idea of giving up the bishop and then placing the pawn on a dark square doesn't appeal much to me. After such obvious sequence as} 8. Nd2 Nd7 9. a4 Ngf6 10. Nc4 Rc8 11. Ke2 $16 {I find it rather obvious that White has a huge advantage that will increase even more when we go Be3, a4-a5, Rhd1, etc.}  ) 8. Ke2 e6 9. Bf4 ( 10. a4 {seems a bit more natural to me, why commit the position of the c1-bishop yet?} Ngf6 11. a5 $16 {Next up, the classic Nd2-c4 will be played. Later, we can go g2-g3, Bg2 and f2-f4, grabbing even more space!}  ) Ne7 10. g3 {I am not sure if I am fully approving of what White did during the last two moves, but the bishops are a long-term asset, so it's not likely he can really spoil his position.} Ng6 11. Bd2 h5 12. Bc3 h4 13. Nd2 Nge5 14. Bg2 O-O-O ( h3 $1 {would have generated enough counterplay.} 15. Bf1 f6 {The h3-pawn is making things a bit ugly, especially not that Black hopes to get some ...g7-g5-g4 in. Perhaps here he could be okay}  ) 15. f4 Ng6 16. Nf3 Be7 17. Bh3 hxg3 18. hxg3 Bf6 19. e5 $16 {Okay, now Black is no longer fine, since now White has managed to completely coordinate and stabilize his position. Later, Andreikin went on to win this game in a rather good style, especially given the fast time control. 1-0 (46) Andreikin,D (2726) -Adly,A (2615) chess. com INT 2020}  ) 7. Ne1 $1 {As usual, we are offering that trade. The knight is headed on d3. To be honest, I really fail to comprehend why most people keep playing various moves here, since when you have studied this line for a very long time, it is rather obvious that the knight belongs exactly on d3 and nowhere else.} Bxe2+ 8. Kxe2 e6 ( e5 9. f3 f6 10. Nd3 $36 {Now, we will see an excellent model game later in the chapter.}  ) 9. Nd3 Nc5 10. f3 Nxd3 11. cxd3 {This pawn structure is somewhat unusual, yet it's good, since the d3-pawn hopes to make it to d4, but even if it doesn't, it is still well-placed and can never get weak due to our wonderful active king.} Bc5 12. Nd2 Ne7 13. Nc4 O-O-O 14. Rb1 {Soon, White will launch a queenside offensive.} Ng6 15. b4 Bd4 16. Bd2 Ne5 17. Rhc1 Nxc4 18. Rxc4 a6 19. a4 $36 {At this point, it is kind of obvious White is owning the board, even though later he didn't find a way to break through and drew. Yet, I don't see any reasons to be upset with the opening outcome!: 1/2 (44) Hovhannisyan,R (2642) -Molina,R (2434) chess.com INT 2020}  *

