1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 dxe4 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 Nf6 $1 {Oh boy, this has been the toughest nut to crack by far, especially given the powerful ideas Black has on the next move. So far, he's simply attacking our pawn on e4.} 6. Nfd2 $1 {Here, Black has to know what he's doing or else he will end up under a serious amount of pressure. The best moves, as I wholeheartedly believe, are ...g7-g5 and ...h7-h5!} ( 7. Nc3 {I don't like this idea at all since White wants to get c2-c3 and Kc2 in.} Bg4 8. Be2 Nbd7 9. Be3 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 e6 {Because the c3-knight is so misplaced, it's not possible to stop ...Bc5, I don't think we have any advantage here (even though, obviously, we can still play this!)}  ) ( 7. Nbd2 {Makes the c1-bishop and the f3-knight rather said. As I keep emphasizing, we need to get f2-f3 in, and we need that really badly. But how will we get the job done after this move?}  ) h5 $1 {The h-pawn push (just as the a-pawn push) has become the golden standard of Leela Zero, the modern engine that shook the chess world so hard lately with a bunch of fantastic discoveries. It also happens to be the move Erwin L'Ami, a very strong theoretician from the Netherlands, happens to recommend in his Chessable course "Lifetime Repertoires: The Caro-Cann". This is the move I've had the hardest time challenging, but I am happy with the final result!} ( g6 7. f3 {Again, I fail to believe Black can equalize in a conventional manner.} Bg7 8. c3 {The g7-bishop is again heavily restrained by the c3-pawn.} O-O 9. a4 Rd8 10. Kc2 c5 {Black wanted to develop the knight to c6. A natural desire, it's hard to blame him! However, now the b5-square and the d5-square are even weaker.} 11. Na3 Nc6 12. Ndc4 Be6 13. Be3 Nd7 14. Be2 Rac8 15. Rhd1 Nce5 16. a5 $16 {In my opinion, this is another example of how White should handle the arising queenless middlegame. His game is flowing so-so smoothly! Later he blundered and lost, but it's blitz, things happen. What matters is that Black's opening was a clear failure! 0-1 (56) Quesada Perez,Y (2598) -Sevian,S (2660) Lichess.org INT 2020}  ) ( e5 $6 {This is a perfect example of what I mean when I say Black will end up under the long-lasting positional pressure if he doesn't play precisely.} 7. f3 Be6 8. Bc4 Bxc4 9. Nxc4 Nfd7 {And White obtained the classic positional advantage that we have already discussed and easily went on to win.} 10. Be3 $16 {1-0 (31) Gavrilescu,D (2476) -Baldauf,M (2503) chess.com INT 2020} ( 11. a4 $16 {Would have been as good}  )  ) ( g5 $5 {This move was introduced by Gorshtein in a game vs Puranik, but got popular after Wei Yi used it versus Karjakin. Since then, it was seen in 10 games, most of which have been played in 2020. Black anticipates the fact we want to go f2-f3, so he's ready to meet this with some ...g5-g4 and ...h7-h5!} 7. a4 {As usual, we don't mind grabbing a ton of queenside space when possible.} g4 8. Nc3 {This is one of the VERY rare examples where I would recommend to play Nc3. We usually hope to get c2-c3 and Kd1-c2 in, however, in this position, it makes perfect sense to develop the knight on c3 as our king will find a perfect haven on e2. Or on c1, if the bishops get traded (you'll see rather soon what I mean) . I believe, at this point it's not very obvious how Black should continue.} h5 ( Bh6 $5 {I believe this is a rather interesting idea, aimed at trading the bishop that usually don't help Black all that much.} 9. a5 {First, we'll improve the situation on the queenside a bit.} Be6 ( Rg8 10. Nb3 Bxc1 11. Kxc1 {Again, possibility of h2-h3 makes White's position extremely comfortable, as we got grip both on the queenside (big thanks to the a4-a5 push!) and on the kingside (the g4-pawn is a target) .}  ) 10. h3 $1 {Now, time to hit the kingside.} gxh3 11. g3 Bg4+ 12. Be2 Be6 13. Nf3 $16 {The h3-pawn will soon be lost, we are doing great.} Bxc1 14. Kxc1 Nbd7 ( Bg4 15. Nd2 Bxe2 16. Nxe2 $14 { Next we will win the h3-pawn and reach the somewhat better endgame due to the superior pawn structure.}  ) 15. Nd4 $16  ) 9. a5 $146 ( 10. Nc4 {Has been played twice, but after} Be6 11. a5 Nbd7 {I am not sure if White is getting anywhere}  ) Be6 {The whole point of delaying Nc4 is that now we can instead go} 10. Bc4 $1 Bxc4 11. Nxc4 Nbd7 {Now, even Ke2 would be very strong, but it's even better to continue} 12. h3 $1 {And open up the h-file.} Rg8 13. hxg4 hxg4 14. Ke2 $16 {White enjoys the typical large advantage, ideas like Be3, Ra3-b3 or a4-b4 are yet to hit Black hard quite soon.}  ) 7. h4 {For now, we simply stop Black's idea of ...h5-h4. This is exactly what Carlsen, Harikrishna, Erdos and Antipov have done in this position as White - hopefully, you agree you're in a good company!} Be6 {Erwin L'Ami believes this is the best solution for Black.} ( Ng4 8. Ke1 e5 9. Nc4 $14 {Feels like the standard nice advantage, since we will just go f2-f3, c2-c3, Be3, a2-a4, Nbd2, etc.}  ) 8. f3 Nfd7 ( Nbd7 $146 9. Nb3 $36 {Now it feels that the Black pieces are positioned in a rather odd way, especially the f8-bishop that now cannot easily get out (as we said, the g7-square isn't a good spot for this bishop) . Also, Nd4 is coming, trapping the e6-bishop - this clearly isn't an attractive position for Black!}  ) 9. Bc4 {I agree White may not be getting much here according to the engines, but it definitely feels that White's position is easier to handle.} ( 10. Nc4 {Is also something I'd suggest you investigate.}  ) ( 10. Nb3 {For some reason, Erwin L'Ami analyzed only this move, ignoring 9.Bc4, which was played by Carlsen and 9.Nc4, which is a very natural way to play.}  ) Nc5 {The engine believes this is the more precise way to play and after} ( Bxc4 10. Nxc4 e5 11. a4 f6 12. Ke2 $16 {Again, White got this typical nagging edge and went on to win! So, the arising positions definitely aren't easy for Black at all. 1-0 (64) Carlsen,M (2863) -Svane,R (2613) Lichess.org INT 2020}  ) 10. Bxe6 Nxe6 11. Nc4 Nd7 12. Be3 {It claims Black is coming close to equalizing, but even if so, White's position is still clearly nicer after} g6 13. a4 Bh6 14. Ke2 Bf4 15. a5 {While Leela or some super-GM may not find this position a big deal, I would definitely take White who is still pressing on the queenside due to his lovely space advantage and the better-organized minor pieces!}  *

