{Now, it's time to look at some really good model games!} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 dxe4 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 {If you don't mind, I will quote my own explanations from the theoretical part as well to make sure you repeat and understand all the ideas very well.} g6 {Quite a lot of players, including MVL who did this twice, tried developing the bishop to the long diagonal. However, as practice shows, the bishop isn't well-placed there, since the c3-pawn would be restricting it a lot. In fact, now I like a very interesting idea that doesn't seem obvious at all.} 6. Ne5 {Only two games saw this move, but I believe it is best. Why are we making it? Well, the thing is that we want to play Be3, but getting hit by the eventual ...Ng4 is no bueno, so we nee f2-f3 in. But that knight is misplaced on f3! So, we are re-routing the knight.} Bg7 7. Nd3 Nf6 8. f3 O-O 9. a4 {Grabbing space on the queenside is another very typical idea.} ( 10. c3 {Obviously, there's nothing wrong with c2-c3 first. Or with Be3 first, or with something else first - the position is very versatile. Later, we simply want to play Kc2, Be3, Nbd2, a2-a4-a5 and reach a very nice position with pressure on the queenside where the g7-bishop will remain a passive and silent spectator.}  ) Nfd7 10. Bg5 {I am not sure how much I like this move, since the bishop wants to be on e3, anyway. I guess forcing ... Bf6 isn't that bad, just as ...Re8, but the normal Be3 is completely fine as well.} Bf6 11. Be3 Ne5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. c3 Be6 14. Nd2 Nd7 15. Kc2 {Alright, now the optimal setup has been achieved! What do we do next? Next up, we should play either Bc4 to trade the only good bishop Black has and to leave him with a sad useless dark-squared one, or keep rolling with Be2, a4-a5, b2-b4, etc. I prefer the first plan.} Bd6 16. Bc4 {The aforementioned plan in action. In the theoretical part, we've cut the analysis short more or less here, but I believe it'd be great to see a bit more to better understand how White should convert his hard-earned advantage.} Bxc4 17. Nxc4 Bc7 18. Rhd1 Rfd8 19. h3 {Very importantly, Black has several problems. 1) he would like to use his king, but it's far away from the main course of action. 2) he would like to fight for the d-file, but his a8-rook is stuck since the a7-pawn is hanging. 3) if he ever goes ...a7-a5, the pawn will be a fixed target pretty much forever. 4) if he ever goes ...a7-a6, the a5-square, the b6-square and the b7-pawn will still stay weak for a very long time. 5) he has no ideas, while White can keep improving his position on the kingside with g2-g4, on the queenside with b2-b4 and create threats with Na5 at some point, or just Rd1-d2, Ra1-d1, etc.} f6 20. Rd2 Kf7 21. h4 $6 {I am not sure about this move as it placed the pawn on a dark square. It feels g2-g4 or just Rad1 would be better.} a6 22. f4 h5 ( b5 $1 {Would have been a good attempt to get counterplay. For instance, after} 23. axb5 cxb5 ( axb5 $4 24. Rxa8 Rxa8 25. Rxd7 $18  ) 24. Na5 Bb6 {Black isn't doing that terrible, though the position like} 25. Bxb6 Nxb6 26. Rxd8 Rxd8 27. b3 $14 {still feels nicer for White as the a6-pawn is quite weakish and the White king is more active. The extra kingside space doesn't hurt, either.}  ) 23. a5 f5 24. exf5 $6 {Now the g-file is open and the g2-pawn is vulnerable. Also, unfortunately, the squares on e4 and d5 are weak and the Black knight can use them, so I am afraid the advantage is nearly gone.} ( 25. Ra3 $1 {would have been incredibly powerful, as there's no stopping of Rb3!, since ...Rb8 would lose to Ba7!} fxe4 26. Rb3 $1 $18 { and the position is collapsing.}  ) gxf5 25. Rad1 $2 {Now the advantage is gone, for sure.} ( 26. Ra3 $1 {More specifically, there was still a chance to get an advantage by means of this move, as the same idea of Rb3 would still rock.}  ) Nf6 26. Ne5+ Ke8 27. b4 Bxe5 28. fxe5 {The position was quite balanced and here Black had to trade himself} Ne4 $2 {this creates a serious issue.} ( Rxd2+ $1 29. Rxd2 Ne4 30. Rd1 e6 $1 {would have kept the roughly equal position.}  ) 29. Rxd8+ Rxd8 30. Rxd8+ Kxd8 31. e6 $1 $18 {Oops! Suddenly the e7-pawn is fixed as a target, the king is stuck inside and the White king is simply walking in the middle of Black's position, things are just falling apart instantly.} Ke8 32. Kd3 Kf8 33. Bg5 c5 34. Bf4 $6 {Not sure if this move is as precise, but White is still winning and later he converted. Not a flawless game, but we need to keep in mind it's impossible to play flawlessly, but we have definitely learned a thing or two from this game!} ( 35. Bh6+ $1 {would have been even more precise as it would have kept the king stuck inside.} Ke8 36. Kc4 cxb4 37. cxb4 { And White's king would win every single pawn Black has.}  ) Kg7 35. Be5+ Kg6 36. Ke3 cxb4 37. cxb4 Nf6 38. Kd4 f4 39. Kc5 Kf5 40. Bxf6 Kxf6 41. Kb6 Kxe6 42. Kxb7 Kf5 43. b5 axb5 44. a6 Kg4 45. a7 Kg3 46. a8=Q Kxg2 47. Kb6+ f3 48. Kxb5 Kg3 49. Kc4 f2 50. Qh1 {1-0 (50) Gavrilescu,D (2473) -Olsen,F (2332) Hamburg 2020}  *

