{Here's another great model game I'd like to offer to your attention. It was played back when we had OTB tournaments, so a long enough time ago, but also, just in 2019 when this 3.d3 line appeared, so not too long ago!} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 dxe4 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 Bg4 {As I had explained in the theoretical chapter, this variation is aimed at pinning the knight and stopping White from going Ne1-d3 and f2-f3. Since Black is interested in castling long fast, this has been the main move. But, to be honest, I don't really see how long castling is supposed to help him THAT much. Fair enough, his king isn't well-placed is the center, even less so on the kingside. On the queenside, instead, it'd help Black stop the invasion and expansion we are planning by means of a4-a5, Nc4, etc. However, his position still won't be fantastic.} 6. Be2 Nd7 7. Ne1 {As usual, we are offering that trade. The knight is headed on d3. To be honest, I really fail to comprehend why most people keep playing various moves here, since when you have studied this line for a very long time, it is rather obvious that the knight belongs exactly on d3 and nowhere else.} Bxe2+ 8. Kxe2 e5 {Now, we have this symmetrical position. How come White can try to claim any advantage, what would it consist of? Well, first off, let's look at the pawn structure. The fact that the light-squared bishops are traded means that the side who will place pawns on the light squares will have the better bishop. Who will be this side? Naturally, because we have the central pawn fixed on e4 (another one's coming to f3 soon) , as opposed to the opponent who has a pawn on e5 (and likely, on f6) , it'll be us! Also, if we play Be3, the a7-pawn is likely to be a problem, since the a8-rook will be stuck defending it, while if the pawn moves, it might either get weak (when it's on a5) , or, at least, the squares on the queenside will get rather weak (look at the b6-square, for instance) . The fact that the pawn is on c6 is also weakening the d6-square, while also, possibly, making the b6-square a potential weakness. So, while we cannot claim a HUGE advantage, I definitely like our position! Let's see how White outplayed the opponent from here.} 9. f3 f6 10. Nd3 Nc5 11. Be3 ( 12. Nxc5 {Was also a possible way to play in order to keep the structure intact and later kick that c5-bishop away with} Bxc5 13. Nd2 Ne7 14. Nb3 Bb6 {and now gain some space} 15. a4 $1 Kf7 16. a5 $1 Bc7 17. Be3 $36 {With a rather nice and obvious strategic initiative due to the beter bishop and advantage on the queenside (the a5-pawn is really helpful, while the b7-pawn might be weak and vulnerable to Nc5!) .}  ) Nxd3 12. cxd3 $5 {This is a rather interesting decision, even though I cannot say I personally like it as much as the idea of keeping the structure symmetrical and putting pressure on Black's queenside. Since this game, the position also occured in two more games. White also took on d3 with the pawn in both of them and won all three!} ( 13. Kxd3 {also was a perfectly reasonable way to play, but White wanted something a bit different.}  ) Bd6 13. Nd2 Ne7 14. Nc4 {Please note that the d3-pawn isn't backward or weak. First off, it can always go to d4. Secondly, Black cannot attack it. And finally, White always has a king and rooks that could defend it if needed!} Kd7 15. Rhc1 Rhb8 16. a4 Ng6 17. a5 ( 18. g3 {would have been my choice. The idea is simple - we want that knight stuck on g6!}  ) Bc7 ( Nf4+ {was a possibility here. For example, after} 18. Bxf4 exf4 19. Nxd6 Kxd6 20. Rc4 $14 {White would keep a clear initiative in the rook endgame, but if you ask me if it was neccessary to trade the minor pieces and allow for ...Nf4+ in the first place, I'd strongly doubt it.}  ) 18. g3 Nf8 19. f4 exf4 20. gxf4 g6 21. Rg1 ( 22. f5 $5 {Was a very interesting decision that could open up some files on the kingside and take the e6-square away both from the Black king and the Black knight!}  ) Re8 22. Kf3 a6 $6 {Now the b7-pawn is extremely vulnerable and the b6-square isn't a great thing for Black, either.} 23. Ra3 Rad8 24. Bd4 ( 25. h4 $1 {Looked tempting as well, trying to open up the g-file or the h-file with h4-h5!}  ) Ke7 25. Bc5+ Kf7 26. Bxf8 {Time for some massive transformations!} Kxf8 27. Rb3 Re7 28. Rd1 Bb8 29. d4 Ba7 30. d5 f5 31. exf5 Rxd5 32. Rxd5 cxd5 33. f6 Re6 34. Ne5 Bd4 35. Rxb7 {The position has changed a lot, White has transformed his positional advantage into the material one as well as into the more active rook. Later, he converted it rather smoothly! Again, I believe there are numerous things we can learn from this game, both structure-wise and when it comes to specific maneuveres, pawn breaks, storms, weak squares, and so on. Such games help improve not just your opening, but your game overall! 1-0 (77) Alekseenko,K (2715) -Pelletier,Y (2561) Budva 2019}  *

